 from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Legh","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Leigh  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Leigh","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of numerous places (in at least sixteen counties, but especially Leigh in Lancashire) named either with the nominative case of Old English <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’ (see   Lee  ) or with <i>lēage</i>, a late dative form of this word (see   Lye  ).","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surname 李, based on its Cantonese pronunciation. See   Li   1."]}]},{"name":"Hugh","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Hugues</i>, <i>Hugo</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>hug</i> ‘heart, mind, spirit’. It was originally a short form of various compound names containing this element. This was borne by the aristocracy of medieval France, adopted by the Normans, and introduced by them to Britain. It was consistently one of the most popular boys' names in the Middle Ages in England, but fell out of favour in the 16th century until it was revived in the 20th century. Little Hugh of Lincoln was a child supposed in the Middle Ages to have been murdered by Jews in about  1255 , a legend responsible for several outbursts of anti-Semitism at various times. The story is referred to by  Chaucer  in The Prioress's Tale. He is not to be confused with  St Hugh of Lincoln  (  1140–1200 ), bishop of Lincoln (  1186–1200 ), who was noted for his charity and good works, his piety, and his defence of the Church against the State. Since the later Middle Ages <i>Hugh</i> has also been used as an Anglicized form of the Gaelic name Aodh ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Hugh de Legh was born in 1126, in Thurleigh, Bedfordshire, England, United Kingdom as the son of Baron Hamon de Venables. He married Beatrice Glanville about 1151, in Bedfordshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1151, in his hometown, at the age of 25."},"et":{"1126–1151":"1126–1151","1130–Male":"1130–Surnud","1128–Female":"1128–Surnud","1156–1217":"1156–1217","1112–1160":"1112–1160","1217":"1217","about 1151":"umbes 1151","1128":"1128","1126":"1126","1112":"1112","1156":"1156","1130":"1130","1151":"1151","1160":"1160","Bedfordshire, England":"Bedfordshire, England","Thurleigh, Bedfordshire, England":"Thurleigh, Bedfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1126–1151":"1126–1151","1130–Male":"1130–Kuollut","1128–Female":"1128–Kuollut","1156–1217":"1156–1217","1112–1160":"1112–1160","1217":"1217","about 1151":"noin 1151","1128":"1128","1126":"1126","1112":"1112","1156":"1156","1130":"1130","1151":"1151","1160":"1160","Bedfordshire, England":"Bedfordshire, England","Thurleigh, Bedfordshire, England":"Thurleigh, Bedfordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1126–1151":"1126–1151","1130–Male":"1130–Décédé","1128–Female":"1128–Décédée","1156–1217":"1156–1217","1112–1160":"1112–1160","1217":"1217","about 1151":"environ 1151","1128":"1128","1126":"1126","1112":"1112","1156":"1156","1130":"1130","1151":"1151","1160":"1160","Bedfordshire, England":"Bedfordshire, Angleterre","Thurleigh, Bedfordshire, England":"Thurleigh, Bedfordshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Hugh de Legh est né en 1126, à Thurleigh, Bedfordshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni, fils de Baron Hamon de Venables. Il a épousé Beatrice Glanville environ 1151, à Bedfordshire, Angleterre. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fils. Il est décédé en 1151, dans sa ville natale, à l’âge de 25 ans."},"de":{"1126–1151":"1126–1151","1130–Male":"1130–Verstorben","1128–Female":"1128–Verstorben","1156–1217":"1156–1217","1112–1160":"1112–1160","1217":"1217","about 1151":"um 1151","1128":"1128","1126":"1126","1112":"1112","1156":"1156","1130":"1130","115